Jakarta EE, javax, And A Week Of Turmoil 

By now, most of you will already know that JEE formerly Java EE, now Jakarta EE hit a little roadblock with the javax package name. During a week of turmoil, many people have written about the matter and this post summaries the communitys opinions, what options do you have and gives you plenty of links to follow up.

 
 
 
 
 

Java Text Blocks

The raw Strings literal has been withdrawn from Java 12 as it did not cover the right set of tradeoffs between complexity and expressiveness to be added in the language.
A new JEP candidate called "Text Blocks" has been added instead trying to simplify both:
      Expressing strings that span several lines of source code
    . Denoting code written in non-Java languages
Take a peek at the new JEP preview!

 
 
 
 
 
 

There Is Always More to Learn

 
 
 
 
 

Handling Exceptions Functional Style 

Java supports checked exceptions from the very start. With Java 8 the language element lambda and the RT library modifications supporting stream operations introduced functional programming style to the language. Functional style and exceptions, however, are not really good friends. In this article by our colleague Peter Verhas, you will check a simple library that handles exceptions somehow similar to how null is handled using Optional.

 
 
 
 
 

Encryption in Java

If you are responsible for the security of your application, there is quite a big chance you end up dealing with encryption at some point. In these two articles, you will get familiar with the basics of Symmetric Encryption and Public Key/Private Key Encryption, grasp their concepts and differences in order to understand what limitations each of them come with.
Part 1: Symmetric Encryption
Part 2: Public Key/Private Key Encryption

 
 
 
 
 

The Matter of time() 

As software engineers, we all rely on the notion of time: a crucial concept in ensuring that events in our programs follow a chronological order. Yet, invoking a simple call to get the current time can potentially yield unexpected results and lead to unforeseen consequences if not used correctly. In this article, you will go through the different ways you can obtain the current time in your programs, and several cases where your intuitions and expectations of time from these clocks may mislead you at best or cause catastrophic failures at worst.

 
 
 
 
 

Local Type Inference Cheat Sheet for Java 10 and Beyond

Using var for declarations can improve code by reducing clutter, thereby letting more important information stand out. On the other hand, applying var indiscriminately can make things worse. This article can serve you as a cheatsheet for the matter, offering many guidelines, principles and example cases. Check it out to start using var properply and improve your code, making it shorter and clearer without compromising understandability.

 
 
 
 
 
 
 

Joining Strings in Java 8: with StringJoiner and String.join

Joining strings in Java has caused a lot of boilerplate code to be written since ages. Moreover you had to be careful with String concatenation in a loop. See how you can address this starting with Java 8!
Moreover you can see how newer Java versions include runtime intrinsics to provide even more performant strings concatenation.

 
 
 
 
 
 
 

Containers: Orchestration and Beyond 

From the introduction of Docker to LXC to Kubernetes, the world of containers has been constantly evolving and it is not going to slow down any time soon. As the adoption of containers and their counterparts increases drastically, engineers and enterprises have had to increasingly put work into ensuring not only container security but also general functionality and maintenance. See this guide to learn major orchestration trends, Kubernetes security, and more!

 
 
 
 
 
 

How to Move Beyond a Monolithic Data Lake to a Distributed Data Mesh

Current big data architectures are evolving from centralised data lake towards modern distributed architecture: considering domains as the first class concern, applying platform thinking to create self-serve data infrastructure, and treating data as a product.
This third generation of data and intelligence platforms is addressing some of the gaps of the previous generations such as real-time data analytics, as well as reducing the cost of managing big data infrastructure. Take a look how you can make the step forward from both technical and organisational perspective.

Reactive Transactions with Spring 

At the time reactive integrations in Spring emerged there was no need for reactive transaction management as it was not supported by underlying databases. 
However this has changed recently with R2DBC and MongoDB 4.0.
Finally we can have @Transational support for reactive integrations too!

 
 
 
 
 
 

Test-Driven Development: Really, Its a Design Technique

Usually we are used to see test-driven development (TDD) as an established technique for delivering better software, more rapidly, and more sustainably over time by enforcing discipline for covering the implementation with tests.
What you might forget is TDD is really a technique for designing systems from the ground up in an emergent manner.
Don't miss this article if you want to improve your existing design by applying focused approach and striving for simplicity.

 
 
 
 

Property-based Testing in Java: PBT and Test-driven Development 

If you ever wondered what is the best testing approach in functional languages you would find out that  functional programming folks are very much into properties as opposed to what OO programmers call unit tests.
Java 8 has shifted our attention (at least a bit) towards functional programming style. Now you can apply the property based testing approach in Java as well with a library called jqwik!
